{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 21:05:05.172066", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Diagnostic report — Clos EBGP fabric (summary of findings)\n\n1) Executive summary\n- The fabric’s control-plane (BGP) appears healthy: routers show expected EBGP neighbors and prefixes, and most hosts can reach remote subnets.\n- There is a localized data-plane anomaly affecting pod 0, leaf_router_0_0 and its directly connected host pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2). The leaf shows a kernel \"blackhole\" route for 10.0.0.0/24 which is inconsistent with the router’s interface and FRR’s BGP state. This mismatch causes traffic from/to pc_0_0 to be dropped (pc_0_0 cannot reach other pods).\n- Impact is limited to the host(s) behind leaf_router_0_0 (pc_0_0); the rest of the topology (other leaves, spines, super-spine) is advertising and receiving routes normally.\n\n2) Observed symptoms and evidence\n- Host-level symptom:\n  - pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2/24) failed pings to remote addresses. Example: ping from pc_0_0 to 10.3.5.2 timed out (ping command timed out).\n  - pc_0_1 and many other hosts had successful pings to the same remote addresses (reachability summary returned many \"ok\" results for other PCs).\n- Interface & addressing:\n  - pc_0_0: eth0 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1\n  - leaf_router_0_0: eth8 10.0.0.1/24 (connected to pc_0_0) — interface present and up.\n    (from get_host_net_config outputs: leaf_router_0_0 eth8 = 10.0.0.1/24)\n- Routing inconsistency on leaf_router_0_0:\n  - The host route table for leaf_router_0_0 contains an explicit blackhole for 10.0.0.0/24 (e.g., \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/24\" present in ip route output).\n  - At the same time FRRBGP on leaf_router_0_0 shows the prefix 10.0.0.0/24 present and locally originated (FRR BGP table shows \"*> 10.0.0.0/24 0.0.0.0 ... i\"), and eth8 is assigned 10.0.0.1/24.\n  - This indicates a control-plane (FRR) belief that the prefix is advertised/connected, but the kernel dataplane has a blackhole installed for that same prefix.\n- Attempts to test from leaf_router_0_0:\n  - A ping attempt from leaf_router_0_0 to 10.0.0.2 returned an error (\"ping: connect: Invalid argument\" via the tool), suggesting the host-based ping attempt failed/unusable from the tool environment; but the key dataplane evidence is the blackhole route + pc_0_0 timeouts.\n- BGP and network health elsewhere:\n  - Spines and super-spine show full view of prefixes and multi-path nexthops as expected. Many BGP tables show the expected 10.x.0.0/24 networks and multiple nexthops; overall BGP topology is converged.\n\n3) Localization — faulty device(s) and impacted segments\n- Primary affected device: leaf_router_0_0.\n  - Evidence: presence of kernel blackhole route for 10.0.0.0/24 on leaf_router_0_0 while interface eth8 is 10.0.0.1/24 and FRR advertises 10.0.0.0/24.\n- Impacted host(s):\n  - pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) — traffic to/from remote networks fails.\n  - Any other device using leaf_router_0_0’s 10.0.0.0/24 would be similarly affected.\n- Non-impacted devices:\n  - pc_0_1 and other pods/leaves/spines/super-spine appear to be functioning normally (reachability tests and routing tables indicate full connectivity).\n\n4) Root-cause analysis (most likely)\n- The immediate root cause of the outage for pc_0_0 is a kernel-level blackhole route for the 10.0.0.0/24 prefix on leaf_router_0_0. This blackhole causes packets destined to/from that subnet to be dropped locally at the leaf, producing the observed host reachability failures.\n- The blackhole is in conflict with the expected connected route (eth8: 10.0.0.1/24) and with FRR’s control-plane advertisement of the prefix. That indicates a control-plane / kernel state mismatch:\n  - FRR believes the prefix is present and is advertising it via BGP.\n  - The kernel routing table has an explicit unreachable/blackhole for the same prefix (so data-plane forwarding is blocked).\n- Possible origins of the blackhole (diagnostic hypotheses, not mitigations):\n  - A prior administrative command installed an IP blackhole for that subnet on the router (static blackhole route).\n  - A previous FRR or kernel event inserted an unreachable route (e.g., a failed netlink update, or automatic behavior after interface down/up), leaving a stale/unintended blackhole.\n  - A local policy (rp_filter, iptables, route-map) interacted with route installation; however, no direct evidence of firewall rules was collected yet.\n  - No evidence in the collected BGP tables that another device is intentionally overriding the prefix — BGP control-plane shows the prefix as local and advertised.\n\n5) Impact assessment\n- Isolation: issue is localized to one leaf and its attached host(s). The rest of the fabric remains functional; interpod and spine-super-spine routing / BGP appears converged and multi-path as expected.\n- Severity: host-level loss of connectivity for pc_0_0 and any services hosted on that /24; potential for traffic blackholes (packets dropped at leaf) if any traffic tries to egress/ingress that host network.\n\n6) Relevant excerpts (evidence)\n- pc_0_0 config: eth0 10.0.0.2/24, gw 10.0.0.1.\n- leaf_router_0_0 interfaces: eth8 10.0.0.1/24 (connected to pc_0_0).\n- leaf_router_0_0 ip route: a kernel-installed \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/24\" entry present.\n- leaf_router_0_0 FRR/BGP: FRR shows the prefix 10.0.0.0/24 in BGP table and indicates it as originated locally (0.0.0.0 next-hop).\n- Reachability: ping from pc_0_0 to 10.3.5.2 timed out while many other PCs could reach that address successfully.\n\n7) Recommended next diagnostic data to collect (if you want to continue troubleshooting)\n- On leaf_router_0_0:\n  - Show full kernel route table (ip route show table main) to confirm precedence and timestamps of blackhole vs connected.\n  - Check for static routes: show running config / ip route entries in FRR and system config that might install a blackhole.\n  - dmesg / syslog around the time the blackhole was created to see any kernel/IF events.\n  - ip -s neigh / arp entries to confirm L2 reachability on eth8.\n  - Verify rp_filter / sysctl settings and any iptables/nft rules that could affect forwarding.\n- From pc_0_0:\n  - tcpdump on pc_0_0 and on leaf_router_0_0 eth8 to confirm whether traffic leaves the host and whether replies reach the leaf.\n- From leaf_router_0_0 control-plane:\n  - FRR logs (zebra/bgpd) to inspect route installation events (why/when the blackhole was created).\n- If needed, temporarily show the output of \"ip route get <ip>\" from the leaf to demonstrate specific forwarding decision for a remote destination.\n\n8) Conclusion\n- The network control-plane (BGP) is mostly healthy and converged, but a control-plane / kernel data-plane mismatch on leaf_router_0_0 (explicit blackhole for 10.0.0.0/24) is causing loss of connectivity for pc_0_0. The anomaly is localized to leaf_router_0_0; root cause is the blackhole route present in the kernel routing table that overrides/blocks the connected prefix.\n\nIf you want, I can run the specific diagnostic commands listed in (7) on leaf_router_0_0 and pc_0_0 to collect the additional evidence. (I will not apply any remediation changes unless you ask.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 50268, "output_tokens": 3680, "total_tokens": 53948, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 48768}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1792}}}
